erial foundation of state power in the region.   As Kinzley argues, Xinjiang's role in producing various natural resources for regional powers has been an important but largely overlooked factor in fueling unrest. He carefully traces the buildup to this unstable situation over the course of the twentieth century by focusing on the shifting priorities of Chinese, Soviet, and provincial officials regarding the production of various resources, including gold, furs, and oil among others. Through his archival work, Kinzley offers a new way of viewing Xinjiang that will shape the conversation about this important region and offer a model for understanding the development of other frontier zones in China as well as across the global south.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aIndustrializationzChina. 0aNatural resourceszChinazXinjiang Uygur Zizhiqu. 4aRussian Empire. 4aSoviet Union. 4aXinjiang. 4aborders. 4ainfrastructure. 4amateriality. 4amodern China. 4anatural resources. 4aoil. 4astate building. 70(DE-601)1043468840(DE-588)4066399-1aWirtschaft2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226492322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226492322.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles